            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe is ten, at a family barbecue in Sacramento. The air is split: on one side, the scent of her dad\u2019s motor oil and the boisterous, booming laughter of her Air Force family; on the other, the softer sound of her mom\u2019s relatives discussing books, smelling of sun-warmed lawn. Standing between them, plate in hand, she feels invisible and hyper-aware. This was the day she learned to listen not just to conversations, but to the silence between them. It was the birth of the observer.\n\n2.\nThe dot-com bust, 2001. The newspaper office felt like a morgue. Her editor, a man whose approval she craved, couldn't meet her eye as he handed her the severance packet. Walking out into the Berkeley sunlight, the weight of her now-useless press pass felt heavier than her student loans. It wasn't just failure; it was the cold, hard death of her idealism. That disillusionment forged an unshakeable resolve to never again be so financially vulnerable, planting the seeds of her pragmatism.\n\n3.\nIt is 2 AM in a cubicle, circa 2003. Drowning in survey data for a new soda brand, her exhausted eyes saw it: a pattern. Not just numbers, but a story of desire and identity hidden in the columns. A narrative of a specific consumer emerged so clearly she could almost hear their voice. In that florescent hum, she felt the same thrill of discovery she\u2019d chased as a reporter. This was when she realized she hadn't abandoned storytelling; she had just found a new, more predictive language for it.\n\n4.\nA Tuesday night, four years ago. Her first year in the Hayes Valley condo, post-divorce. She stood by the window with a glass of Pinot, watching the N-Judah streetcar glide by, its lights painting streaks on her wall. There was no ache of loneliness, only a profound, quiet stillness. This\u2014the view, the wine, the silence\u2014wasn\u2019t inherited or shared. It was earned. This moment cemented her sense of self-reliance, a comfort she had built entirely on her own terms.\n\n5.\nLast year, during a high-stakes quarterly review. A junior analyst, a sharp young woman of color, presented brilliant data but faltered under the aggressive questioning of a senior director. Kira saw her own past insecurities reflected in the analyst\u2019s eyes. In that moment, her own success felt hollow. It wasn\u2019t enough to have a seat at the table. This crystalized her next chapter: she had to use her position to change the dynamics of the room itself."
